The model specified in(17)conforms to the properties of the data described intable 2. Specifically, ARCH effects are captured in the
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $A^{*}_{11}$ \end{document}
               and
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $B^{*}_{11}$ \end{document}
               coefficient matrices, whereas the elements of the
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $D^{*}_{11}$ \end{document}
               matrix capture asymmetric responses to innovations in returns and volume. Finally, we extend the existing literature by relaxing the implicit assumption that the impact of all trades is equal; here, a short sale will alter the dynamics of volatility if any or all of the elements of
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $E^{*}_{11}$ \end{document}
               are significant.

Quasi–maximum likelihood estimation of the model given inequation (17)provided the individual parameter estimates that are reported intable 3along with the associated robust standard errors (see Bollerslev and Wooldridge1992). The estimates of the main‐diagonal elements of \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $A^{*}_{11}$ \end{document} are significant in all cases, indicating that past return (volume) volatility affects current volatility in returns (volume) as is typical of GARCH processes. Except for Henderson, the off‐diagonal elements of \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $A^{*}_{11}$ \end{document} are generally significant and suggest that volatility transmissions exist between volume and returns for these five companies. The significance of all the estimated main‐diagonal elements in the \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $B^{*}_{11}$ \end{document} matrix indicates that past innovations to returns and volume are significant determinants of current volatility. Further, the significance of the off‐diagonal elements in the \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $B^{*}_{11}$ \end{document} matrix for Cathay and HSBC suggests that innovations in returns affect the volatility of volume and vice versa. Overall, these results are suggestive of a nonlinear feedback loop in which volume acts as a proxy for the news that drives volatility. These volatility innovations in turn reveal information to the market, motivating further trades and so increasing volume. Table 3
